Project 1: "PharmAgent" — autonomous drug safety intelligence system
The elevator pitch
PharmAgent is an agentic RAG system that autonomously cross-references FDA drug labels, biomedical literature, and clinical guidelines to answer complex pharmacovigilance questions like "Is metformin safe for a 68-year-old patient with stage 3 CKD who is already taking lisinopril and warfarin?" Unlike vanilla RAG, PharmAgent decomposes this multi-part question into sub-queries, retrieves from three distinct knowledge sources, grades document relevance, self-corrects when retrieval fails, and synthesizes a cited safety assessment — all without human intervention. It reduces the drug safety review workflow from 2–4 hours of manual cross-referencing to under 60 seconds.
Why agentic RAG is the right architecture (not just a demo)
Vanilla RAG fails catastrophically on this problem. A single retrieve-and-generate pass cannot handle queries that require multi-hop reasoning across heterogeneous sources. Consider the query above: the agent must (1) identify the three drugs involved, (2) check each drug's label for renal dosing adjustments, (3) cross-reference drug-drug interactions between all three, (4) retrieve clinical guidelines for CKD-specific contraindications, and (5) verify its synthesis against the primary sources. This is a control loop, not a pipeline.
Agentic RAG adds four capabilities that vanilla RAG lacks and that this problem demands:

Query decomposition: Breaks "Is this drug combination safe for this patient?" into 4–6 targeted sub-queries across different knowledge bases
Dynamic tool routing: Decides whether to search the drug label vector store, the PubMed literature index, or the clinical guidelines index — or all three — based on the sub-query type
Self-correction with document grading: If retrieved chunks are irrelevant (e.g., wrong drug formulation), the agent rewrites the query and re-retrieves rather than hallucinating MediumMeilisearch
Hallucination verification: Post-generation check ensures every safety claim is grounded in a source document — critical in a domain where a wrong answer could harm patients

The arXiv survey on Agentic RAG (Singh et al., 2501.09136) identifies this exact pattern — reflection, planning, tool use, and multi-source retrieval — as the canonical architecture for safety-critical domains. arXiv
Real-world business problem and stakeholders
Problem: Pharmacovigilance analysts at pharmaceutical companies and hospital pharmacy departments spend 2–4 hours per complex drug safety review, manually searching FDA labels on DailyMed, cross-referencing interaction databases, and reviewing PubMed literature. A Twitch/Amazon case study showed that similar multi-source knowledge work had 20% of questions going unanswered due to information scattered across systems, with 2-hour average response times. AWS
Stakeholders: Hospital pharmacists conducting medication reconciliation, pharmaceutical company safety officers reviewing adverse event signals, clinical researchers evaluating drug combinations for trials, and regulatory affairs teams preparing FDA submissions.
