Key business metrics and KPIs

Drug safety review time: Target reduction from 2–4 hours to under 60 seconds per query (>95% time savings)
Retrieval precision@10: Measure using RAGAS Context Precision — target >0.75 across all three knowledge sources
Faithfulness score: RAGAS Faithfulness metric — target >0.90, ensuring every safety claim is grounded in source documents
Hallucination rate: Target <6% (benchmarked against the 5.8% achieved by self-reflective RAG Kanda Software in the 2025 MDPI clinical study)
Multi-hop accuracy: Percentage of multi-drug interaction queries answered correctly vs. pharmacist ground truth — target >85%
Query decomposition success rate: Percentage of complex queries correctly decomposed into valid sub-queries
Self-correction trigger rate: How often the agent rewrites queries after grading retrieved docs as irrelevant (indicates the system is working, not failing)

Technical architecture overview
The system uses LangGraph to orchestrate a stateful agent with six nodes in a cyclic graph:
Node 1 — Query Analyzer & Router: Classifies the incoming query (single-drug lookup, multi-drug interaction, patient-specific safety check) and determines which knowledge sources to query. Uses Llama 3.1 8B via Groq for fast, cheap classification.
Node 2 — Multi-Source Retriever (ToolNode): Three retrieval tools registered as LangGraph tools: (a) drug label vector store (DailyMed chunks in ChromaDB), (b) PubMed literature index (MedRAG snippets in a second ChromaDB collection), (c) clinical guidelines index (StatPearls in a third collection). The agent selects which tools to invoke based on sub-query type. Implements hybrid search (BM25 + dense vectors via Reciprocal Rank Fusion) for each collection. Superlinked
Node 3 — Document Grader: LLM evaluates each retrieved chunk for relevance to the specific sub-query. Irrelevant chunks are discarded. If insufficient relevant documents remain, routes back to Node 4. Rahul kolekar
Node 4 — Query Rewriter: Reformulates failed sub-queries with more specific terms Meilisearch and re-routes to Node 2. Rahul kolekar Maximum 2 retry loops to prevent infinite cycling (budget cap).
Node 5 — Synthesis Generator: Llama 3.3 70B via Groq synthesizes the graded, relevant chunks into a structured safety assessment with inline citations. Output format: risk level, supporting evidence, contraindications, recommended monitoring.
Node 6 — Hallucination & Answer Grader: Verifies (a) the answer is grounded in retrieved sources (faithfulness check) and (b) the answer actually addresses the original question. Failed checks route back to Node 5 with corrective instructions. Rahul kolekar
Cross-encoder reranking (sentence-transformers cross-encoder model) is applied between Nodes 2 and 3 for improved retrieval precision. DEV Community Langfuse (open-source, self-hosted) provides observability with traces of every agent decision, retrieval, and generation step.
